Reference is now made to a brief description of the drawings, which are intended to illustrate an arterial catheter system for use herein. The drawings and detailed description which follow are intended to be merely illustrative and are not intended to limit the scope of the invention as set forth in the appended claims.


FIG. 1 is a longitudinal view of an arterial catheter system having its distal end positioned in the ascending aorta during use;


FIG. 2 is a longitudinal view of an arterial catheter system for use as depicted in FIG. 1, shown without a surrounding vessel;


FIG. 2A is a cross-sectional view of the catheter depicted in FIG. 2 shown through section line 2A--2A;


FIG. 3 depicts an atherectomy cutting assembly for use in an arterial catheter system as disclosed herein;


FIG. 4 depicts an atherectomy cutting assembly for use in an arterial catheter system as disclosed herein;


FIG. 4A depicts an atherectomy cutting assembly having an adjustable orifice;


FIG. 5 depicts an atherectomy cutting assembly as shown in FIG. 3 having a mobile aortic plaque engaged by the cutting assembly;


FIG. 6 depicts an atherectomy cutting assembly for use in an arterial catheter system as disclosed herein;


FIG. 7A depicts a cutting blade which is received by the housing of FIG. 7 to comprise a cutting assembly for use in an arterial catheter system as disclosed herein;


FIG. 8 is a longitudinal view of an arterial catheter system having its distal end positioned in the ascending aorta, and using a snare as a trapping mechanism for mobile aortic plaque;


FIG. 9A depicts an atherectomy assembly in accordance with another embodiment having a basket with an adjustable opening at a distal end;


FIG. 9B depicts the atherectomy assembly of FIG. 9A in a collapsed condition;


FIG. 10 depicts an atherectomy cutting assembly having a adjustable orifice for trapping plaque and a cutting blade operably disposed beneath the adjustable orifice;


FIG. 11A depicts an atherectomy assembly in accordance with another embodiment, and having claws which operate to grab plaque material;


FIG. 11B depicts the atherectomy assembly of FIG. 11A, in an open condition;


FIG. 12A depicts an atherectomy assembly in accordance with another embodiment, having partial spherical surfaces which pivot to close upon plaque material;


FIG. 12B depicts the atherectomy assembly of FIG. 12A in the closed condition;


FIG. 12C depicts the atherectomy assembly of FIG. 12B as viewed from its distal tip;


FIG. 13A depicts an atherectomy assembly in accordance with another embodiment, having more than one window to receive plaque material;


FIG. 13B depicts the atherectomy assembly of FIG. 13A viewed from above;


FIG. 13C depicts the atherectomy assembly of FIG. 13B with the cutting assembly translated to close off windows which receive plaque;


FIG. 14A depicts an atherectomy assembly in accordance with another embodiment, having a basket and a cutting wire or snare to excise plaque material;


FIGS. 14B, 14C, and 14D show a top view of the atherectomy assembly depicted in 14A, with activation of a cutting wire to excise plaque;


FIG. 15A shows an atherectomy assembly in an alternative embodiment, having forward grabbing capabilities, while FIG. 15B depicts the atherectomy assembly in an open configuration;


FIGS. 16A and 16B show an atherectomy assembly in an alternative embodiment, viewed from a side and from above;


FIG. 16C shows the atherectomy assembly of FIG. 16A as viewed from its distal end, while FIG. 16D shows the atherectomy assembly of FIG. 16C in a closed configuration;


FIG. 17 is a longitudinal view of an arterial catheter system for use in the carotid arteries;


FIG. 18 depicts a filtering and positioning atherectomy guide catheter;


FIG. 19 depicts a positioning atherectomy guide catheter;


FIG. 20 depicts an atherectomy catheter having an atherectomy assembly as shown in FIGS. 14A-14D, including positioning struts;


FIGS. 21 and 21A depict an atherectomy catheter deployed in the aortic arch and using positioning struts to deflect away from plaque;


FIGS. 22 and 22A depict an atherectomy catheter having clamping fingers and associated mesh for forward removal of plaque; and


FIGS. 23 and 23A depict an atherectomy catheter having plaque retention means.
